<div class="tool-seo">
  <h2>How to Use This JSON Formatter</h2>
  <p>Paste or type your JSON into the input box above and click <strong>Format</strong> to beautify it with proper indentation. Click <strong>Minify</strong> to compress it into a single line. Click <strong>Validate</strong> to check for syntax errors — the tool will show you the exact line and column where the error occurs.</p>

  <h2>Common JSON Formatting Issues</h2>
  <p>JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is the standard data format for APIs and configuration files. Common issues include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Trailing commas</strong> — JSON does not allow trailing commas after the last item in an object or array</li>
    <li><strong>Single quotes</strong> — JSON requires double quotes for strings and keys</li>
    <li><strong>Unquoted keys</strong> — All keys must be wrapped in double quotes</li>
    <li><strong>Comments</strong> — Standard JSON does not support comments (// or /* */)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>JSON vs JSON5</h2>
  <p>This tool validates standard JSON (RFC 8259). If you need features like trailing commas, unquoted keys, or comments, consider using JSON5 instead. However, most APIs and config parsers expect standard JSON.</p>
</div>

